description:
An expansion to 18Ruhr, allowing players to cut the playable map in half. It also adds the following things:


     two new private companies;
     mixed Montan companies, allowing both coal and steel mines simultaneously;
     new tiles;
     the Dortmunder Hafenbahn, an additional (industrial) railway.

Along with the crew of the Dream-chaser, several of Middle-earth's greatest heroes must once more sail the wild seas south of the Grey Havens. Their journey will take them through jagged reefs and raging squalls. They will confront corsairs and risk falling overboard, and all in a desperate effort to reclaim a stolen relic&hellip;

Set after the events of The Grey Havens deluxe expansion, Flight of the Stormcaller introduces a new scenario that allows you to embark upon a dramatic, high-stakes chase across the stormy seas. Your heroes join the crew of the Dream-chaser and the other ships in her fleet, and they must battle through treacherous waters, foul weather, and Corsair ships to close upon the Stormcaller, the powerful vessel commanded by the ferocious Captain Sah&iacute;r. Time is of the essence, and if your heroes can't catch the Stormcaller, they'll forfeit their only link to the forsaken realm of N&uacute;menor.

Along with this unique scenario, which features quests decks for the players and for the Corsairs, Flight of the Stormcaller introduces a new Leadership hero and three copies each of ten different player cards. Altogether, its sixty new cards carry us far across uncharted waters, support decks designed to run with fewer than three heroes, reinforce the enduring strengths of the Gondor trait, and boast a handful of unique allies and events that plunge us deep into the cycle's new themes and mechanics.

During game setup, the Spooky Ghost is placed in the room next to &ldquo;>= 9.&rdquo;

During gameplay, if the Spooky Ghost is on the same storey as any other playing piece, the Ghost &ldquo;steals&rdquo; one die from the active player. This means the player has a maximum of only three dice for that throw of their turn. After that throw is resolved, the player must move the Spooky Ghost one storey up or down.

This extension was on the back of the catalogue of family Games from Haba.

The Vampires team has won the HELVETIA Cup many times before. Strongly hierarchical and deceptively strong, the Vampires are not that tough, but they should be approached with caution.
Their motto: "One for all and all for me!"
In this box, you&rsquo;ll find the necessary to play the Vampires Team: 9 pre-painted miniatures, Player Cards, POWER Cards, &hellip;

On an archaeological expedition, you discover the ancient tome of riddles that you had long been searching for&mdash;sadly, its pages are torn to shreds beyond hope of reassembly. Your hopes dashed, you decide to raise your spirits by using the fragments of riddles that remain to hold a contest of wits and riddle-making with your friends at the local tavern&hellip;

As players lay down cards, a single riddle slowly gets more and more complicated. You must decide whether to add more to the riddle or to challenge someone to answer it.
You can choose some of the riddle&rsquo;s clues, but don&rsquo;t get caught without an answer!

"Despite all our hopes, Earth got depleted before FTL jumps were possible. However, mankind made one last and desperate effort: five colony fleets were sent in an intergenerational journey to other worlds potentially capable of supporting human life&hellip;

...colonists reaching Arcturus found a barren planet, and in order to preserve their very existence they established a symbiotic relationship with the ancient supercomputer they found there&hellip;

...those reaching Draco incorporated the genes of an indigenous lizard into their DNA so they could survive the adverse planetary conditions&hellip;

...colonists headed for Kerberos found resources were scarce there and chose to change themselves so no one had to be left behind&hellip;

...as for the fourth fleet... well, you all know what happened... let's just say that we were the lucky ones, especially considering that no one has heard about the fifth fleet ever since.

One would think the later invention of the FTL drive presented an opportunity to reunite and live in peace with our long lost brothers... unfortunately, regardless of our many differences, we all were descendants of mankind and thus we all were afflicted by the same curse: WAR".


Parallax is a 4X board game, playable in 2 to 3 hours, which focuses on providing a deep political space opera experience.

The political part is achieved through variable player powers and asymmetric factions: since each player exploits the monopoly of a different resource and handles crucial information only available to their faction, chances are that not only they will need to eXplore, eXpand, eXploit and eXterminate to meet their goals, but to also negotiate or even become allies to do so.

This, combined with the fact that every decision affects the unstable balance of power, not only allows for constant player interaction but also eliminates downtime, since everyone has some influence over each other actions &mdash;to the point of even affecting the outcome of battles and duels they are not directly involved in&mdash;.

As for the space opera part, it is achieved by putting the spotlight on the characters that the players use to carry out their orders, on the personal relationships that arise between them and on how they affect the global conflict: for example, your commodore may be hesitant to attack the fleet commanded by the person she just fell in love with in the previous turn, and she may even deflect if forced to do so.

This not only allows for a rich dramatic narrative that makes each game memorable, but also presents players with a series of events that force them to constantly reassess their alliances, further fostering negotiation and player interaction.

Don&rsquo;t miss the opportunity to not only participate in galactic diplomacy, empire building and interplanetary battles, but to also become part of the romance and the drama experienced by their protagonists... Join us to spy on your fellow diplomats and sell the information to the highest bidder, to persuade local leaders to support you in the upcoming elections, or to taste the glory of becoming champion of the arena&hellip; just make sure that, when the time comes, you&rsquo;re in the winning alliance&hellip;

From the publisher:

&ldquo;This planet is a hellhole, but it&rsquo;ll be an Imperial hellhole when we&rsquo;re through with it.&rdquo;
   &ndash;Lieutenant Zhaebin, Vostroyan Firstborn

Jungles of Nectavus is the first War Pack in the Death World cycle for Warhammer 40,000: Conquest.

For much of the Imperium, a Death World is a place you will never see&mdash;and never want to see. On Nectavus VI, the entire planet is covered by jungle, and everything in that jungle is trying to kill you. The trees and vines spray poisonous spikes at whatever comes near. The animals that dwell within the jungle can strike invisibly from the shadows or simply use their brute strength and unreasoning resilience to crush their foes. Nectavus VI is an unquestionable Death World, yet it is about to become the site of another massive battle for the Traxis sector&hellip;

Jungles of Nectavus is the first War Pack in the Death World cycle, and as such, it serves as an introduction to the themes and mechanics that pervade the rest of the cycle. Here, every faction enters the jungles of Nectavus VI, and you&rsquo;ll need to embrace new tactics to survive in such a hostile environment. On this world, drawing attention to yourself can be a death sentence, so a new keyword allows you to deploy your cards secretly, only revealing them as the battle is about to begin. The Death World cycle also brings a new focus to each factions&rsquo; Elite units, making them a more integral part of your armies than ever before!

&ldquo;Honey, what's inside the sandwiches? I think the roastbeef is trying to flee away.&rdquo; 
&ldquo;WHAT? You are kidding me! &hellip; What?&rdquo; &ldquo;ANTS! FURMIIIIIIIIIIS!&rdquo;

Sparafurmiis is a game for 2 &ndash; 4 players inspired by the messy arrival of a little gang of bugs viciously attacking an unaware family out for a Sunday's pic-nic. Take command of the ant soldiers assisted with a siege catapult, made of ice cream sticks, and supported by mobile spiders and birds that hunt the opponent spiders. Get as many crumbs as you can before your opponent! 
A dexterity and tactical game for all the family, mixing ballistic coordination with movement on the chess-style tablecloth.
